Packages and Help

1 Learning Objectives

  • Know how to install R packages from CRAN
  • Understand how to use packages and functions in R
  • Know how to use the RStudio help file function

Lesson Duration: 1 hour

As we discussed earlier, one of the strengths of R is the huge ecosystem of packages available.

Using an R package gives you access to extra functions and data.

2 Installing a package

  • Before you start, remember to set-up a project.

You can think about a package the same way as any piece of software that comes from the internet. Before you can use the software you need to download and install it.

To install a package we use the function install.packages:

install.packages("RXKCD")

We only need to install a package once. Once it’s installed we can tell R that we want to use it like this

library(RXKCD)

Note

  • You only need to do the first step once! Once a package is installed you don“t need to install it again. You can think of installing the package like downloading and installing RStudio. Once you”ve done that once you only need to click on it to open. Using library is the equivalent of clicking on a program.

  • You need quotes (") for installing, but not for loading.

3 Using a package

Once you"ve installed a package and loaded the library all the functions in that library are available for you to use.

searchXKCD and getXKCD are two functions from inside RXKCD.

  • searchXKCD searches through XKCD comics and finds comics that have the string you search for in their title or transcript.

  • getXKCD gets an XKCD comic by number and searches displays in for you.

Let"s try this out now. Remember your keyboard shortcuts for creating a code chunk and running a code chunk.

searchXKCD("data")
getXKCD(373)

Now, try let“s restart the R session. This”refresh" R, and will remove all the packages we"ve loaded in using library.

  • Go to Session > Restart R

Now try run the two chunks again.

We have errors because R doesn’t know about the two functions any more.

3.1 Why do we need packages?

Task - Class Discussion - 5 minutes

Why do we need to load packages? Couldn’t we have every function from every package already loaded in R?

Let’s install a new package.

install.packages("lubridate")

The warning message when loading this package gives a hint about why

library(lubridate)
## 
## Attaching package: 'lubridate'
## The following object is masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     date

The warning message you saw says that an “object” is “masked”. When you loaded in lubridate, the inbuilt functions date in R is overwritten by one from lubridate with the same name. Basically, there"s only so many different names that functions can have!

Its easy to expect a certain function, but actually end up with a different one if you have too many libraries loaded.

You can check which functions are being masked with the functions conflicts.

conflicts()
##  [1] "Arith"       "Compare"     "show"        "as.difftime" "body<-"     
##  [6] "date"        "intersect"   "kronecker"   "setdiff"     "union"

3.2 The packages panel

In the bottom left quadrant of RStudio of of the tabs is the ‘Packages’ panel. It shows you which packages you have installed. Clicking on a package will take you to the help files for that package.

You can install packages or update packages using the commands at the top of the panel. You can also load a package by clicking on the tick box next to the package. However, we would strongly recommend loading packages by using library calls in your scripts. It can be easy to forget what packages you’ve loaded, and your analysis won’t run the next time you open it without the packages loaded.

3.3 The base package

The R functions that come without installing any packages is what is normally called “base R”. There are actually several core packages that make up the base including “base”, “stats”, “methods”, so that“s why the warning talks about”package:base".

3.4 Warnings vs. errors

The red message you saw when you loaded the lubridate package was a warning. This is R telling you there is a problem, but not so big a problem it couldn’t run the code you asked for.

The red message you saw after refreshing and trying to run functions from RXKCD is an error. Here R is telling you about a problem that“s so big it can”t run the code.

3.5 Using a function from a package

If you only need a function or two out of a package then you can specify a specific function by using a double colon:

RXKCD::searchXKCD("data")
  • Restart your R session again so that RXKCD definitely isn’t loaded and try running the function above using double colon notation.
RXKCD::getXKCD(605)

This time the function will run, even though RXKCD isn’t loaded, because we specified which package they were in.

4 Getting Help

Every function, including all the base R functions and functions from packages, has a help file associated with it. If you aren’t sure how to use a function you can look up the help file by using a question mark and the function name.

?median

Note that you don"t need brackets after the function name.

The help pages for functions can be a little overwhelming if you“re not used to reading them. We”ll break down the help file for median.

  • Description - All help files start with a description of the function. Sometimes these can be a little difficult to understand.

  • Usage - This is one of the most useful parts of a help page. It shows you the function with all the arguments available.

Arguments without an equals sign are mandatory, you have to give them a value.

Arguments with an equal sign afterwards are optional, if you don"t specify them they will default to the value after the equals sign.

  • Arguments - This gives you more detail about the arguments to the function, in particular what type of object they need to be.

  • Details - This gives extra information about the function. Sometimes this section is very useful.

  • Value - This tells you what type of object the function will return.

  • Examples - This can be the most useful part of the help file. This shows you some examples of the function being used. Sometimes it helps to start with this part of the help file.

You can also get help about any of the inbuilt datasets.

?mtcars

Look at the help file for min. What do you notice?

?min

Sometimes functions share their help files with other functions, particularly if the functions share a related idea.

4.1 Help for a package

Each package has it’s own help page too:

help(package = "RXKCD")

Task - 10 minutes

Using the package beepr, get R to play a the noise of a fanfare. You will need to read the help files to do this.

Solution

install.packages("beepr")
library(beepr)
beep("fanfare")

5 The Class Data Package

We’ve put together a special R package, which contains just datasets that you’ll be using in the course. You need to install the data in a slightly different way from usual, because the package is only stored on GitHub and not on CRAN - the central official hub for R packages.

Luckily, it’s still easy to install the package. First you need to install devtools.

install.packages('devtools')

Then use the function install_github from the devtools package.

devtools::install_github('codeclan/CodeClanData')
library(CodeClanData)
## 
## Attaching package: 'CodeClanData'
## The following object is masked from 'package:datasets':
## 
##     volcano

To use any dataset in the package, you can just call it by name.

students
